	(13, 1, 'Vsq9DlD3VpQ', 'DAILY CATHOLIC MASS 3/21/26 | The Captivating Presence: Recognizing Christ Amidst the Crowd', 'daily-catholic-mass-32126-the-captivating-presence-recognizing-christ-amidst-the-crowd', 'Welcome! Join The CatholicTV Network for the full Daily Catholic Mass celebration on this Saturday of the Fourth Week of Lent. We are especially pleased to welcome the "Christ Crew" students from Cardinal Spellman High School to our chapel today.\n\nIn today’s moving Homily, Father Paul Ring reflects on the captivating and charismatic presence of Jesus, whose words "strike the heart" and "overwhelm us". Drawing from the trials of the Prophet Jeremiah and the divisions in the Gospel crowd, Father Ring explores why Jesus is far beyond any prophet who came before Him. We are reminded that while the Pharisees were threatened and "entrenched in the letter of the law," we are called to be like Nicodemus—drawn by Christ\'s very personhood to seek a secret and deep relationship with Him. This Mass is a powerful invitation to allow the Lord’s presence to "take root" in us so that we may share His light with everyone we meet as we approach Holy Week.\n\nThe Scriptures highlight the vulnerability of God\'s messengers and the mystery of the Messiah:\n-The First Reading (Jeremiah 11:18-20): The prophet Jeremiah describes himself as a "trusting lamb led to slaughter," unaware of the plots hatched against him by those wishing to "destroy the tree in its vigor". He entrusts his cause to the Lord, the "just judge" and "searcher of mind and heart".\n-The Responsorial Psalm (Ps 7): A cry for protection: "O Lord, my God, in you I take refuge".\n-The Holy Gospel (John 7:40-53): A division occurs in the crowd over Jesus’ identity—some see Him as the Prophet, others as the Christ. Even the temple guards are spellbound, reporting to the Pharisees: "Never before has anyone spoken like this man". Despite the Pharisees\' rejection, Nicodemus stands up for justice, questioning if the law condemns a man before hearing him.\n\nMay these holy gifts purify us and render us fully pleasing to God as we continue our journey toward the joy of the Resurrection.\n\nMass Chapters for Navigation\n\n-Introductory Rites / Penitential Act: 0:58\n-Collect (Opening Prayer): 2:24\n-First Reading: 2:54\n-Responsorial Psalm: 3:40\n-Gospel: 6:23\n-Homily: 7:47\n-Prayers Of The Faithful: 14:31\n-Liturgy of the Eucharist Begins: 15:55\n-Eucharistic Prayer / Consecration: 17:21\n-The Lord\'s Prayer: 22:02\n-Communion: 24:09\n-Concluding Rites / Final Blessing: 26:51\n\nTheological & Liturgical Context\n-Season: Saturday of the Fourth Week of Lent.\n-Gospel Focus: The Uniqueness of Christ; Jesus’ presence is so powerful that even those sent to arrest Him are unable to lay hands on Him, revealing that His authority is not derived from worldly status but from His personhood as the Lamb of God.\n-Homily Key Message: We are called to "trust that the Lord\'s presence may abide in us"; Lent is our time to deepen this relationship through prayer and fasting, ensuring that when we reach the Culmination of the Paschal Feast, we do so with "joy of minds made pure".\n\nIf today\'s Mass helped you feel the captivating presence of Jesus, please Like this video and Subscribe to The CatholicTV Network. Your support allows us to continue bringing the victory of Jesus over death to our global family!\n\nSubscribe to our YouTube channel so you never miss a daily Mass: http://bit.ly/31Ceiuu\n\nJoin this channel to get access to perks like custom CatholicTV emojis:\nhttps://www.youtube.com/channel/UCORAZZmab8apqy2TMHZlZVQ/join\n\nDonate to CatholicTV and join us in our mission: https://www.catholictv.org/donate\nCatholicTV website: http://bit.ly/2KlLFuX\nLike us on Facebook: http://bit.ly/2LWw1tm\nFollow us on Twitter: http://bit.ly/31eG1lf\nFollow us on Instagram: http://bit.ly/339rEAf\n\n#CatholicMass #DailyMass #Lent2026 #GospelOfJohn #ProphetJeremiah #LambOfGod #SpiritualGrowth #CharismaticJesus #Catholic #Theology #VirtualMass #CatholicTV #FatherPaulRing', 'https://i.ytimg.com/vi/Vsq9DlD3VpQ/maxresdefault.jpg', '2026-03-21 03:00:23', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Vsq9DlD3VpQ', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/Vsq9DlD3VpQ', 'PT28M48S', 14514, 0, 12, '{"id": "Vsq9DlD3VpQ", "etag": "RipNcPVk1XBYQbcIIWs5xtSQFhM", "kind": "youtube#video", "snippet": {"tags": ["daily Mass", "Catholic", "tv mass", "streaming mass", "roman catholic", "youtube mass", "archdiocese of boston mass", "todays mass", "online liturgy", "Saturday Mass", "Father Paul Ring"], "title": "DAILY CATHOLIC MASS 3/21/26 | The Captivating Presence: Recognizing Christ Amidst the Crowd", "channelId": "UCORAZZmab8apqy2TMHZlZVQ", "localized": {"title": "DAILY CATHOLIC MASS 3/21/26 | The Captivating Presence: Recognizing Christ Amidst the Crowd", "description": "Welcome! Join The CatholicTV Network for the full Daily Catholic Mass celebration on this Saturday of the Fourth Week of Lent. We are especially pleased to welcome the \\"Christ Crew\\" students from Cardinal Spellman High School to our chapel today.\\n\\nIn today’s moving Homily, Father Paul Ring reflects on the captivating and charismatic presence of Jesus, whose words \\"strike the heart\\" and \\"overwhelm us\\". Drawing from the trials of the Prophet Jeremiah and the divisions in the Gospel crowd, Father Ring explores why Jesus is far beyond any prophet who came before Him. We are reminded that while the Pharisees were threatened and \\"entrenched in the letter of the law,\\" we are called to be like Nicodemus—drawn by Christ\'s very personhood to seek a secret and deep relationship with Him. This Mass is a powerful invitation to allow the Lord’s presence to \\"take root\\" in us so that we may share His light with everyone we meet as we approach Holy Week.\\n\\nThe Scriptures highlight the vulnerability of God\'s messengers and the mystery of the Messiah:\\n-The First Reading (Jeremiah 11:18-20): The prophet Jeremiah describes himself as a \\"trusting lamb led to slaughter,\\" unaware of the plots hatched against him by those wishing to \\"destroy the tree in its vigor\\". He entrusts his cause to the Lord, the \\"just judge\\" and \\"searcher of mind and heart\\".\\n-The Responsorial Psalm (Ps 7): A cry for protection: \\"O Lord, my God, in you I take refuge\\".\\n-The Holy Gospel (John 7:40-53): A division occurs in the crowd over Jesus’ identity—some see Him as the Prophet, others as the Christ. Even the temple guards are spellbound, reporting to the Pharisees: \\"Never before has anyone spoken like this man\\". Despite the Pharisees\' rejection, Nicodemus stands up for justice, questioning if the law condemns a man before hearing him.\\n\\nMay these holy gifts purify us and render us fully pleasing to God as we continue our journey toward the joy of the Resurrection.\\n\\nMass Chapters for Navigation\\n\\n-Introductory Rites / Penitential Act: 0:58\\n-Collect (Opening Prayer): 2:24\\n-First Reading: 2:54\\n-Responsorial Psalm: 3:40\\n-Gospel: 6:23\\n-Homily: 7:47\\n-Prayers Of The Faithful: 14:31\\n-Liturgy of the Eucharist Begins: 15:55\\n-Eucharistic Prayer / Consecration: 17:21\\n-The Lord\'s Prayer: 22:02\\n-Communion: 24:09\\n-Concluding Rites / Final Blessing: 26:51\\n\\nTheological & Liturgical Context\\n-Season: Saturday of the Fourth Week of Lent.\\n-Gospel Focus: The Uniqueness of Christ; Jesus’ presence is so powerful that even those sent to arrest Him are unable to lay hands on Him, revealing that His authority is not derived from worldly status but from His personhood as the Lamb of God.\\n-Homily Key Message: We are called to \\"trust that the Lord\'s presence may abide in us\\"; Lent is our time to deepen this relationship through prayer and fasting, ensuring that when we reach the Culmination of the Paschal Feast, we do so with \\"joy of minds made pure\\".\\n\\nIf today\'s Mass helped you feel the captivating presence of Jesus, please Like this video and Subscribe to The CatholicTV Network. Your support allows us to continue bringing the victory of Jesus over death to our global family!\\n\\nSubscribe to our YouTube channel so you never miss a daily Mass: http://bit.ly/31Ceiuu\\n\\nJoin this channel to get access to perks like custom CatholicTV emojis:\\nhttps://www.youtube.com/channel/UCORAZZmab8apqy2TMHZlZVQ/join\\n\\nDonate to CatholicTV and join us in our mission: https://www.catholictv.org/donate\\nCatholicTV website: http://bit.ly/2KlLFuX\\nLike us on Facebook: http://bit.ly/2LWw1tm\\nFollow us on Twitter: http://bit.ly/31eG1lf\\nFollow us on Instagram: http://bit.ly/339rEAf\\n\\n#CatholicMass #DailyMass #Lent2026 #GospelOfJohn #ProphetJeremiah #LambOfGod #SpiritualGrowth #CharismaticJesus #Catholic #Theology #VirtualMass #CatholicTV #FatherPaulRing"}, "categoryId": "29", "thumbnails": {"high": {"url": "https://i.ytimg.com/vi/Vsq9DlD3VpQ/hqdefault.jpg", "width": 480, "height": 360}, "maxres": {"url": "https://i.ytimg.com/vi/Vsq9DlD3VpQ/maxresdefault.jpg", "width": 1280, "height": 720}, "medium": {"url": "https://i.ytimg.com/vi/Vsq9DlD3VpQ/mqdefault.jpg", "width": 320, "height": 180}, "default": {"url": "https://i.ytimg.com/vi/Vsq9DlD3VpQ/default.jpg", "width": 120, "height": 90}, "standard": {"url": "https://i.ytimg.com/vi/Vsq9DlD3VpQ/sddefault.jpg", "width": 640, "height": 480}}, "description": "Welcome! Join The CatholicTV Network for the full Daily Catholic Mass celebration on this Saturday of the Fourth Week of Lent. We are especially pleased to welcome the \\"Christ Crew\\" students from Cardinal Spellman High School to our chapel today.\\n\\nIn today’s moving Homily, Father Paul Ring reflects on the captivating and charismatic presence of Jesus, whose words \\"strike the heart\\" and \\"overwhelm us\\". Drawing from the trials of the Prophet Jeremiah and the divisions in the Gospel crowd, Father Ring explores why Jesus is far beyond any prophet who came before Him. We are reminded that while the Pharisees were threatened and \\"entrenched in the letter of the law,\\" we are called to be like Nicodemus—drawn by Christ\'s very personhood to seek a secret and deep relationship with Him. This Mass is a powerful invitation to allow the Lord’s presence to \\"take root\\" in us so that we may share His light with everyone we meet as we approach Holy Week.\\n\\nThe Scriptures highlight the vulnerability of God\'s messengers and the mystery of the Messiah:\\n-The First Reading (Jeremiah 11:18-20): The prophet Jeremiah describes himself as a \\"trusting lamb led to slaughter,\\" unaware of the plots hatched against him by those wishing to \\"destroy the tree in its vigor\\". He entrusts his cause to the Lord, the \\"just judge\\" and \\"searcher of mind and heart\\".\\n-The Responsorial Psalm (Ps 7): A cry for protection: \\"O Lord, my God, in you I take refuge\\".\\n-The Holy Gospel (John 7:40-53): A division occurs in the crowd over Jesus’ identity—some see Him as the Prophet, others as the Christ. Even the temple guards are spellbound, reporting to the Pharisees: \\"Never before has anyone spoken like this man\\". Despite the Pharisees\' rejection, Nicodemus stands up for justice, questioning if the law condemns a man before hearing him.\\n\\nMay these holy gifts purify us and render us fully pleasing to God as we continue our journey toward the joy of the Resurrection.\\n\\nMass Chapters for Navigation\\n\\n-Introductory Rites / Penitential Act: 0:58\\n-Collect (Opening Prayer): 2:24\\n-First Reading: 2:54\\n-Responsorial Psalm: 3:40\\n-Gospel: 6:23\\n-Homily: 7:47\\n-Prayers Of The Faithful: 14:31\\n-Liturgy of the Eucharist Begins: 15:55\\n-Eucharistic Prayer / Consecration: 17:21\\n-The Lord\'s Prayer: 22:02\\n-Communion: 24:09\\n-Concluding Rites / Final Blessing: 26:51\\n\\nTheological & Liturgical Context\\n-Season: Saturday of the Fourth Week of Lent.\\n-Gospel Focus: The Uniqueness of Christ; Jesus’ presence is so powerful that even those sent to arrest Him are unable to lay hands on Him, revealing that His authority is not derived from worldly status but from His personhood as the Lamb of God.\\n-Homily Key Message: We are called to \\"trust that the Lord\'s presence may abide in us\\"; Lent is our time to deepen this relationship through prayer and fasting, ensuring that when we reach the Culmination of the Paschal Feast, we do so with \\"joy of minds made pure\\".\\n\\nIf today\'s Mass helped you feel the captivating presence of Jesus, please Like this video and Subscribe to The CatholicTV Network. Your support allows us to continue bringing the victory of Jesus over death to our global family!\\n\\nSubscribe to our YouTube channel so you never miss a daily Mass: http://bit.ly/31Ceiuu\\n\\nJoin this channel to get access to perks like custom CatholicTV emojis:\\nhttps://www.youtube.com/channel/UCORAZZmab8apqy2TMHZlZVQ/join\\n\\nDonate to CatholicTV and join us in our mission: https://www.catholictv.org/donate\\nCatholicTV website: http://bit.ly/2KlLFuX\\nLike us on Facebook: http://bit.ly/2LWw1tm\\nFollow us on Twitter: http://bit.ly/31eG1lf\\nFollow us on Instagram: http://bit.ly/339rEAf\\n\\n#CatholicMass #DailyMass #Lent2026 #GospelOfJohn #ProphetJeremiah #LambOfGod #SpiritualGrowth #CharismaticJesus #Catholic #Theology #VirtualMass #CatholicTV #FatherPaulRing", "publishedAt": "2026-03-21T04:00:23Z", "channelTitle": "The CatholicTV Network", "defaultLanguage": "en", "defaultAudioLanguage": "en-US", "liveBroadcastContent": "none"}, "statistics": {"likeCount": "574", "viewCount": "14514", "commentCount": "109", "favoriteCount": "0"}, "contentDetails": {"caption": "true", "duration": "PT28M48S", "dimension": "2d", "definition": "hd", "projection": "rectangular", "contentRating": [], "licensedContent": false}}', '2026-03-29 09:18:51', '2026-03-29 09:33:12'),
	(14, 1, 'JcohYvjh5fk', 'DAILY CATHOLIC MASS 3/20/26 | Cost of Conviction: Facing Opposition and the Hidden Counsels of God', 'daily-catholic-mass-32026-cost-of-conviction-facing-opposition-and-the-hidden-counsels-of-god', 'Welcome! Join The CatholicTV Network for the full Daily Catholic Mass celebration on this Friday of the Fourth Week of Lent.\n\nIn today’s insightful Homily, Father David O’Leary reflects on the growing tension between Jesus and the authorities of His day as He moves toward the culmination of His mission. Drawing from the Book of Wisdom and the Gospel of John, Father O\'Leary explores the spiritual journey from "ashes to Easter," reminding us that our Lenten observance is meant to change us inwardly and deepen our knowledge of Christ. We are encouraged to see that while the world often judges based on outward origins, we who know "the end of the story"—the Resurrection—are called to live as disciples with a deeper, spiritual sight. This Mass is a powerful invitation to respect the dignity of all believers and to be renewed in holiness of mind and heart.\n\nThe Scriptures highlight the mystery of the "Just One" and the truth of His divine origin:\n-The First Reading (Wisdom 2:1, 12-22): The wicked plot against the just one, finding him "obnoxious" because his life is a reproach to their lawlessness. They decide to test his gentleness with torture and condemn him to a "shameful death," unaware that their wickedness has blinded them to the hidden counsels of God.\n-The Responsorial Psalm (Ps 34): A reminder of God\'s presence in times of trial: "The Lord is close to the brokenhearted".\n-The Holy Gospel (John 7:1-2, 10, 25-30): Jesus travels to Jerusalem for the Feast of Tabernacles in secret because of plots against His life. As He teaches openly in the temple area, the inhabitants wonder if the authorities have realized He is the Christ, though they mistakenly believe they know His origin. Jesus cries out that while they know where He comes from on earth, they do not know the One who is true, who sent Him.\n\nMay the healing effects of these sacred mysteries reflect in our holiness of life as we pass from "old to new" during this holy season.\n\nMass Chapters for Navigation\n\n-Introductory Rites / Penitential Act: 0:58\n-Collect (Opening Prayer): 2:00\n-First Reading: 2:41\n-Responsorial Psalm: 5:42\n-Gospel: 8:10\n-Homily: 9:45\n-Prayers Of The Faithful: 14:21\n-Liturgy of the Eucharist Begins: 15:53\n-Eucharistic Prayer / Consecration: 17:22\n-The Lord\'s Prayer: 23:10\n-Communion: 25:58\n-Concluding Rites / Final Blessing: 27:12\n\nTheological & Liturgical Context\n-Season: Friday of the Fourth Week of Lent.\n-Gospel Focus: The Divine Origin of Jesus; Jesus challenges the crowds’ superficial knowledge of Him, revealing that authentic faith requires recognizing His relationship with the Father, which remains hidden from those who seek only worldly signs.\n-Homily Key Message: We are called to "be changed spiritually" during Lent; by looking past the tensions and opposition faced by Jesus, we find the "crown of glory" and a deeper relationship with our Savior.\n\nIf today\'s Mass helped you reflect on your Lenten journey, please Like this video and Subscribe to The CatholicTV Network. Your support allows us to continue bringing the victory of Jesus over death to our global parish!\n\nSubscribe to our YouTube channel so you never miss a daily Mass: http://bit.ly/31Ceiuu\n\nJoin this channel to get access to perks like custom CatholicTV emojis:\nhttps://www.youtube.com/channel/UCORAZZmab8apqy2TMHZlZVQ/join\n\nDonate to CatholicTV and join us in our mission: https://www.catholictv.org/donate\nCatholicTV website: http://bit.ly/2KlLFuX\nLike us on Facebook: http://bit.ly/2LWw1tm\nFollow us on Twitter: http://bit.ly/31eG1lf\nFollow us on Instagram: http://bit.ly/339rEAf\n\n#CatholicMass #DailyMass #Lent2026 #GospelOfJohn #BookOfWisdom #Discipleship #FaithJourney #Catholic #Theology #VirtualMass #CatholicTV #Fath