	(22, 1, 'iEHHbCt8-d4', 'DAILY CATHOLIC MASS 3/14/26 | The Pharisee, the Tax Collector, and the Mercy of God', 'daily-catholic-mass-31426-the-pharisee-the-tax-collector-and-the-mercy-of-god', 'Welcome! Join The CatholicTV Network for the full Daily Catholic Mass celebration on this Saturday of the Third Week of Lent as we seek the grace to decrease so that Christ may increase in us.\n\nIn today’s stirring Homily, the celebrant reflects on the foundation of all virtues: humility. Drawing from the contrasting prayers of the Pharisee and the Tax Collector, he reminds us that "the way up to heaven is down". We are challenged to move beyond self-righteousness and the tendency to despise others, instead adopting the posture of a child to truly meet Jesus Christ. This Mass is a powerful invitation to present our contrite hearts to our Divine Physician, trusting that His mercy is the only path to being justified in His sight.\n\nThe Scriptures highlight the desire of God for internal conversion over external ritual:\n-The First Reading (Hosea 6:1-6): The prophet calls the people to return to the Lord, trusting that He who has "rent" will also heal and bind our wounds. The passage culminates in a profound theological truth regarding God\'s priority: "For it is love that I desire, not sacrifice, and knowledge of God rather than burnt offerings".\n-The Responsorial Psalm (Ps 51): A humble plea for restoration: "It is mercy I desire, and not sacrifice".\n-The Holy Gospel (Luke 18:9-14): Jesus addresses a parable to those convinced of their own righteousness. He contrasts the Pharisee, who lists his good deeds, with the Tax Collector, who beats his breast and prays, "O God, be merciful to me, a sinner". Jesus declares that the humble Tax Collector went home justified, for "everyone who exalts himself shall be humbled, and the one who humbles himself shall be exalted".\n\nMay these Holy Gifts by which the Lord ceaselessly nourishes us, increase our faith and keep us safe for eternal life.\n\nMass Chapters for Navigation\n\n-Introductory Rites / Penitential Act: 1:06\n-Collect (Opening Prayer): 2:06\n-First Reading: 2:41\n-Responsorial Psalm: 3:49\n-Gospel: 6:30\n-Homily: 8:39\n-Prayers Of The Faithful: 10:51\n-Liturgy of the Eucharist Begins: 12:34\n-Eucharistic Prayer / Consecration: 14:08\n-The Lord\'s Prayer: 20:36\n-Communion: 23:35\n-Concluding Rites / Final Blessing: 26:51\n\nTheological & Liturgical Context\n-Season: Saturday of the Third Week of Lent.\n-Gospel Focus: The Necessity of Humility; Jesus teaches that our standing before God is not earned through a checklist of religious duties but through a sincere acknowledgement of our dependence on His grace.\n-Homily Key Message: We are called to "decrease so that Christ may increase"; our Lenten journey is a time to set our hearts on the Paschal Mystery, allowing God\'s right hand to protect and purify us through our humble entreaty.\n\nIf today’s Mass helped you find peace in God’s mercy, please Like this video and Subscribe to The CatholicTV Network. Your support allows us to continue providing this great prayer that brings benefit to the whole world!\n\nSubscribe to our YouTube channel so you never miss a daily Mass: http://bit.ly/31Ceiuu\n\nJoin this channel to get access to perks like custom CatholicTV emojis:\nhttps://www.youtube.com/channel/UCORAZZmab8apqy2TMHZlZVQ/join\n\nDonate to CatholicTV and join us in our mission: https://www.catholictv.org/donate\nCatholicTV website: http://bit.ly/2KlLFuX\nLike us on Facebook: http://bit.ly/2LWw1tm\nFollow us on Twitter: http://bit.ly/31eG1lf\nFollow us on Instagram: http://bit.ly/339rEAf\n\n#CatholicMass #DailyMass #Lent2026 #GospelOfLuke #ProphetHosea #Humility #PhariseeAndTaxCollector #DivineMercy #Catholic #Theology #VirtualMass #CatholicTV', 'https://i.ytimg.com/vi/iEHHbCt8-d4/maxresdefault.jpg', '2026-03-14 03:00:47', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iEHHbCt8-d4', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/iEHHbCt8-d4', 'PT28M48S', 11822, 0, 21, '{"id": "iEHHbCt8-d4", "etag": "b91Ka6tfuyciYZHLs3bFhWfXAvI", "kind": "youtube#video", "snippet": {"tags": ["daily Mass", "Catholic", "tv mass", "streaming mass", "roman catholic", "youtube mass", "archdiocese of boston mass", "todays mass", "online liturgy", "Saturday Mass", "Father Ixon Chateau"], "title": "DAILY CATHOLIC MASS 3/14/26 | The Pharisee, the Tax Collector, and the Mercy of God", "channelId": "UCORAZZmab8apqy2TMHZlZVQ", "localized": {"title": "DAILY CATHOLIC MASS 3/14/26 | The Pharisee, the Tax Collector, and the Mercy of God", "description": "Welcome! Join The CatholicTV Network for the full Daily Catholic Mass celebration on this Saturday of the Third Week of Lent as we seek the grace to decrease so that Christ may increase in us.\\n\\nIn today’s stirring Homily, the celebrant reflects on the foundation of all virtues: humility. Drawing from the contrasting prayers of the Pharisee and the Tax Collector, he reminds us that \\"the way up to heaven is down\\". We are challenged to move beyond self-righteousness and the tendency to despise others, instead adopting the posture of a child to truly meet Jesus Christ. This Mass is a powerful invitation to present our contrite hearts to our Divine Physician, trusting that His mercy is the only path to being justified in His sight.\\n\\nThe Scriptures highlight the desire of God for internal conversion over external ritual:\\n-The First Reading (Hosea 6:1-6): The prophet calls the people to return to the Lord, trusting that He who has \\"rent\\" will also heal and bind our wounds. The passage culminates in a profound theological truth regarding God\'s priority: \\"For it is love that I desire, not sacrifice, and knowledge of God rather than burnt offerings\\".\\n-The Responsorial Psalm (Ps 51): A humble plea for restoration: \\"It is mercy I desire, and not sacrifice\\".\\n-The Holy Gospel (Luke 18:9-14): Jesus addresses a parable to those convinced of their own righteousness. He contrasts the Pharisee, who lists his good deeds, with the Tax Collector, who beats his breast and prays, \\"O God, be merciful to me, a sinner\\". Jesus declares that the humble Tax Collector went home justified, for \\"everyone who exalts himself shall be humbled, and the one who humbles himself shall be exalted\\".\\n\\nMay these Holy Gifts by which the Lord ceaselessly nourishes us, increase our faith and keep us safe for eternal life.\\n\\nMass Chapters for Navigation\\n\\n-Introductory Rites / Penitential Act: 1:06\\n-Collect (Opening Prayer): 2:06\\n-First Reading: 2:41\\n-Responsorial Psalm: 3:49\\n-Gospel: 6:30\\n-Homily: 8:39\\n-Prayers Of The Faithful: 10:51\\n-Liturgy of the Eucharist Begins: 12:34\\n-Eucharistic Prayer / Consecration: 14:08\\n-The Lord\'s Prayer: 20:36\\n-Communion: 23:35\\n-Concluding Rites / Final Blessing: 26:51\\n\\nTheological & Liturgical Context\\n-Season: Saturday of the Third Week of Lent.\\n-Gospel Focus: The Necessity of Humility; Jesus teaches that our standing before God is not earned through a checklist of religious duties but through a sincere acknowledgement of our dependence on His grace.\\n-Homily Key Message: We are called to \\"decrease so that Christ may increase\\"; our Lenten journey is a time to set our hearts on the Paschal Mystery, allowing God\'s right hand to protect and purify us through our humble entreaty.\\n\\nIf today’s Mass helped you find peace in God’s mercy, please Like this video and Subscribe to The CatholicTV Network. Your support allows us to continue providing this great prayer that brings benefit to the whole world!\\n\\nSubscribe to our YouTube channel so you never miss a daily Mass: http://bit.ly/31Ceiuu\\n\\nJoin this channel to get access to perks like custom CatholicTV emojis:\\nhttps://www.youtube.com/channel/UCORAZZmab8apqy2TMHZlZVQ/join\\n\\nDonate to CatholicTV and join us in our mission: https://www.catholictv.org/donate\\nCatholicTV website: http://bit.ly/2KlLFuX\\nLike us on Facebook: http://bit.ly/2LWw1tm\\nFollow us on Twitter: http://bit.ly/31eG1lf\\nFollow us on Instagram: http://bit.ly/339rEAf\\n\\n#CatholicMass #DailyMass #Lent2026 #GospelOfLuke #ProphetHosea #Humility #PhariseeAndTaxCollector #DivineMercy #Catholic #Theology #VirtualMass #CatholicTV"}, "categoryId": "29", "thumbnails": {"high": {"url": "https://i.ytimg.com/vi/iEHHbCt8-d4/hqdefault.jpg", "width": 480, "height": 360}, "maxres": {"url": "https://i.ytimg.com/vi/iEHHbCt8-d4/maxresdefault.jpg", "width": 1280, "height": 720}, "medium": {"url": "https://i.ytimg.com/vi/iEHHbCt8-d4/mqdefault.jpg", "width": 320, "height": 180}, "default": {"url": "https://i.ytimg.com/vi/iEHHbCt8-d4/default.jpg", "width": 120, "height": 90}, "standard": {"url": "https://i.ytimg.com/vi/iEHHbCt8-d4/sddefault.jpg", "width": 640, "height": 480}}, "description": "Welcome! Join The CatholicTV Network for the full Daily Catholic Mass celebration on this Saturday of the Third Week of Lent as we seek the grace to decrease so that Christ may increase in us.\\n\\nIn today’s stirring Homily, the celebrant reflects on the foundation of all virtues: humility. Drawing from the contrasting prayers of the Pharisee and the Tax Collector, he reminds us that \\"the way up to heaven is down\\". We are challenged to move beyond self-righteousness and the tendency to despise others, instead adopting the posture of a child to truly meet Jesus Christ. This Mass is a powerful invitation to present our contrite hearts to our Divine Physician, trusting that His mercy is the only path to being justified in His sight.\\n\\nThe Scriptures highlight the desire of God for internal conversion over external ritual:\\n-The First Reading (Hosea 6:1-6): The prophet calls the people to return to the Lord, trusting that He who has \\"rent\\" will also heal and bind our wounds. The passage culminates in a profound theological truth regarding God\'s priority: \\"For it is love that I desire, not sacrifice, and knowledge of God rather than burnt offerings\\".\\n-The Responsorial Psalm (Ps 51): A humble plea for restoration: \\"It is mercy I desire, and not sacrifice\\".\\n-The Holy Gospel (Luke 18:9-14): Jesus addresses a parable to those convinced of their own righteousness. He contrasts the Pharisee, who lists his good deeds, with the Tax Collector, who beats his breast and prays, \\"O God, be merciful to me, a sinner\\". Jesus declares that the humble Tax Collector went home justified, for \\"everyone who exalts himself shall be humbled, and the one who humbles himself shall be exalted\\".\\n\\nMay these Holy Gifts by which the Lord ceaselessly nourishes us, increase our faith and keep us safe for eternal life.\\n\\nMass Chapters for Navigation\\n\\n-Introductory Rites / Penitential Act: 1:06\\n-Collect (Opening Prayer): 2:06\\n-First Reading: 2:41\\n-Responsorial Psalm: 3:49\\n-Gospel: 6:30\\n-Homily: 8:39\\n-Prayers Of The Faithful: 10:51\\n-Liturgy of the Eucharist Begins: 12:34\\n-Eucharistic Prayer / Consecration: 14:08\\n-The Lord\'s Prayer: 20:36\\n-Communion: 23:35\\n-Concluding Rites / Final Blessing: 26:51\\n\\nTheological & Liturgical Context\\n-Season: Saturday of the Third Week of Lent.\\n-Gospel Focus: The Necessity of Humility; Jesus teaches that our standing before God is not earned through a checklist of religious duties but through a sincere acknowledgement of our dependence on His grace.\\n-Homily Key Message: We are called to \\"decrease so that Christ may increase\\"; our Lenten journey is a time to set our hearts on the Paschal Mystery, allowing God\'s right hand to protect and purify us through our humble entreaty.\\n\\nIf today’s Mass helped you find peace in God’s mercy, please Like this video and Subscribe to The CatholicTV Network. Your support allows us to continue providing this great prayer that brings benefit to the whole world!\\n\\nSubscribe to our YouTube channel so you never miss a daily Mass: http://bit.ly/31Ceiuu\\n\\nJoin this channel to get access to perks like custom CatholicTV emojis:\\nhttps://www.youtube.com/channel/UCORAZZmab8apqy2TMHZlZVQ/join\\n\\nDonate to CatholicTV and join us in our mission: https://www.catholictv.org/donate\\nCatholicTV website: http://bit.ly/2KlLFuX\\nLike us on Facebook: http://bit.ly/2LWw1tm\\nFollow us on Twitter: http://bit.ly/31eG1lf\\nFollow us on Instagram: http://bit.ly/339rEAf\\n\\n#CatholicMass #DailyMass #Lent2026 #GospelOfLuke #ProphetHosea #Humility #PhariseeAndTaxCollector #DivineMercy #Catholic #Theology #VirtualMass #CatholicTV", "publishedAt": "2026-03-14T04:00:47Z", "channelTitle": "The CatholicTV Network", "defaultLanguage": "en", "defaultAudioLanguage": "en-US", "liveBroadcastContent": "none"}, "statistics": {"likeCount": "534", "viewCount": "11822", "commentCount": "97", "favoriteCount": "0"}, "contentDetails": {"caption": "true", "duration": "PT28M48S", "dimension": "2d", "definition": "hd", "projection": "rectangular", "contentRating": [], "licensedContent": false}}', '2026-03-29 09:18:51', '2026-03-29 09:33:12'),
	(23, 1, '11oUgVTfLBw', 'DAILY CATHOLIC MASS 3/13/26 | The Greatest Commandment: Loving God and Neighbor with One Heart', 'daily-catholic-mass-31326-the-greatest-commandment-loving-god-and-neighbor-with-one-heart', 'Welcome! Join The CatholicTV Network for the full Daily Catholic Mass celebration on this Friday of the Third Week of Lent as we reflect on the heart of the Gospel: the call to total love.\n\nIn today’s reverent Homily, Father Tim Kearney explores the profound unity between our love for God and our love for one another. Reflecting on the scribe’s question to Jesus, Father Kearney reminds us that true worship is not found in external "burnt offerings and sacrifices" alone, but in a heart that is completely surrendered to the Lord. We are encouraged to see that our Lenten practices are meant to draw us away from "unruly desires" and toward a life where God is our sole focus. This Mass is a powerful invitation to "return to the Lord" with a contrite spirit, trusting that He will heal our defection and love us freely.\n\nThe Scriptures highlight the beauty of repentance and the priority of charity:\n-The First Reading (Hosea 14:2-10): The prophet Hosea exhorts Israel to "return to the Lord your God," bringing with them words of repentance rather than empty rituals. The Lord responds with a beautiful promise of restoration: "I will heal their defection, I will love them freely; for my wrath is turned away from them".\n-The Responsorial Psalm (Ps 81): A call to fidelity: "I am the Lord your God: hear my voice".\n-The Holy Gospel (Mark 12:28-34): A scribe asks Jesus which is the first of all the commandments. Jesus responds by citing the Shema: "Love the Lord your God with all your heart, with all your soul, with all your mind, and with all your strength". He adds the second: "You shall love your neighbor as yourself," declaring there is no commandment greater than these.\n\nMay the strength of the Lord be at work in us today, pervading our minds and bodies and bringing us to the fullness of redemption.\n\nMass Chapters for Navigation\n\n-Introductory Rites / Penitential Act: 1:04\n-Collect (Opening Prayer): 2:04\n-First Reading: 2:27\n-Responsorial Psalm: 4:12\n-Gospel: 6:30\n-Homily: 7:40\n-Prayers Of The Faithful: 14:13\n-Liturgy of the Eucharist Begins: 15:30\n-Eucharistic Prayer / Consecration: 17:30\n-The Lord\'s Prayer: 22:23\n-Communion: 24:53\n-Concluding Rites / Final Blessing: 27:31\n\nTheological & Liturgical Context\n-Season: Friday of the Third Week of Lent.\n-Gospel Focus: The Shema and Charity; Jesus reveals that the entirety of the Law and the Prophets is summarized in a single, undivided movement of love toward the Creator and His creation, moving the focus from legalistic observance to a relationship of the heart.\n-Homily Key Message: We pray for the grace to be "constantly drawn away from unruly desires" so that we may obey the heavenly teaching given to us, spreading the gifts of God\'s charity "far and wide".\n\nIf today’s Mass helped you center your life on love, please Like this video and Subscribe to The CatholicTV Network. Your support and donations allow us to continue sharing this great prayer with our global family of faith!\n\nSubscribe to our YouTube channel so you never miss a daily Mass: http://bit.ly/31Ceiuu\n\nJoin this channel to get access to perks like custom CatholicTV emojis:\nhttps://www.youtube.com/channel/UCORAZZmab8apqy2TMHZlZVQ/join\n\nDonate to CatholicTV and join us in our mission: https://www.catholictv.org/donate\nCatholicTV website: http://bit.ly/2KlLFuX\nLike us on Facebook: http://bit.ly/2LWw1tm\nFollow us on Twitter: http://bit.ly/31eG1lf\nFollow us on Instagram: http://bit.ly/339rEAf\n\n#CatholicMass #DailyMass #Lent2026 #GospelOfMark #ProphetHosea #GreatestCommandment #Shema #LoveGod #LoveNeighbor #Catholic #Theology #VirtualMass #CatholicTV #FatherTimKearney', 'https://i.ytimg.com/vi/11oUgVTfLBw/maxresdefault.jpg', '2026-03-13 03:00:02', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=11oUgVTfLBw', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/11oUgVTfLBw', 'PT28M49S', 14444, 0, 22, '{"id": "11oUgVTfLBw", "etag": "g5pGhPE8KQy2Z7gXLT9onSIgr00", "kind": "youtube#video", "snippet": {"tags": ["daily Mass", "Catholic", "tv mass", "streaming mass", "roman catholic", "youtube mass", "archdiocese of boston mass", "todays mass", "online liturgy", "Friday Mass", "Father Timothy Kearney"], "title": "DAILY CATHOLIC MASS 3/13/26 | The Greatest Commandment: Loving God and Neighbor with One Heart", "channelId": "UCORAZZmab8apqy2TMHZlZVQ", "localized": {"title": "DAILY CATHOLIC MASS 3/13/26 | The Greatest Commandment: Loving God and Neighbor with One Heart", "description": "Welcome! Join The CatholicTV Network for the full Daily Catholic Mass celebration on this Friday of the Third Week of Lent as we reflect on the heart of the Gospel: the call to total love.\\n\\nIn today’s reverent Homily, Father Tim Kearney explores the profound unity between our love for God and our love for one another. Reflecting on the scribe’s question to Jesus, Father Kearney reminds us that true worship is not found in external \\"burnt offerings and sacrifices\\" alone, but in a heart that is completely surrendered to the Lord. We are encouraged to see that our Lenten practices are meant to draw us away from \\"unruly desires\\" and toward a life where God is our sole focus. This Mass is a powerful invitation to \\"return to the Lord\\" with a contrite spirit, trusting that He will heal our defection and love us freely.\\n\\nThe Scriptures highlight the beauty of repentance and the priority of charity:\\n-The First Reading (Hosea 14:2-10): The prophet Hosea exhorts Israel to \\"return to the Lord your God,\\" bringing with them words of repentance rather than empty rituals. The Lord responds with a beautiful promise of restoration: \\"I will heal their defection, I will love them freely; for my wrath is turned away from them\\".\\n-The Responsorial Psalm (Ps 81): A call to fidelity: \\"I am the